  <main class="wrap">
    <h1>About Re4ctoR</h1>
    <p>
      Re4ctoR was born from a simple constraint: <strong>some systems cannot afford weak randomness</strong>.
      Blockchains, financial systems and critical infrastructure all depend on entropy that must be not only
      strong, but <em>provably</em> strong and auditable.
    </p>

    <h2>Mission</h2>
    <p>
      Our mission is to provide a <strong>high-assurance randomness and VRF layer</strong> that can stand up to
      cryptographic scrutiny, regulatory audits and real-world attacks — including those coming from a
      post-quantum future.
    </p>

    <h2>Design Principles</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Security first</strong> — fail-closed behaviour, continuous self-tests, strong crypto defaults.</li>
      <li><strong>Transparency</strong> — public test reports, SBOM, and reproducible builds wherever possible.</li>
      <li><strong>Verifiability</strong> — signed outputs and on-chain verification options via Solidity contracts.</li>
      <li><strong>Post-quantum readiness</strong> — support for Dilithium-3 signatures in enterprise builds.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Roadmap & Compliance</h2>
    <p>
      Re4ctoR is designed with FIPS 140-3 entropy requirements and FIPS 204 (post-quantum signatures)
      in mind. While formal certification is a separate process, the architecture, documentation and
      test harnesses are built to align with those standards from day one.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Entropy Source Validation (ESV) packages and health tests.</li>
      <li>BigCrush, Dieharder, PractRand and NIST STS-style batteries.</li>
      <li>SBOM and dependency transparency for supply-chain security.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Who Uses Re4ctoR?</h2>
    <p>
      Re4ctoR is targeting teams that need more than a generic RNG:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Blockchain rollups and L2 sequencers.</li>
      <li>DeFi protocols and on-chain games that demand provable fairness.</li>
      <li>Financial institutions running sensitive key management and simulations.</li>
      <li>Organizations in defense and critical infrastructure preparing for post-quantum threats.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Contact</h2>
